      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanibel%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The Sanibel Lighthouse, standing at the island's eastern tip, anchors the famous fishing pier and nearby nature trails.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanibel%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1832 the Florida Peninsular Land Company founded a settlement called \"Sanybel,\" but it vanished by 1849.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanibel%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The Sanibel Causeway, opened in 1963, replaced a ferry and helped the city incorporate in 1974 while protecting the island’s ecology.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanibel%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "More than half of Sanibel Island lies within wildlife refuges, the largest being the “Ding” Darling National Wildlife Refuge.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18,
        19
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanibel%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "The island’s shell museum, the Bailey‑Matthews National Shell Museum, showcases the region’s famed shelling heritage.",
